snippet.textDisplay:
You know when your parents and aunts and uncles would talk about some entertainer that was big in their day "aint nobody as good as so-and-so, you youngins really missed out"

Dave Chappelle is one of those guys for our generation I think. I have fond memories of me and my childhood best friend watching Killing them Softly and For What It's Worth over and over and over again. We would quote those specials constantly. And then the same thing with Chappelle show.

Then he disappears, his specials just get more and more popular in his absence, and then he comes back as the great unifier in the craziness of post 2016 and quickly gets recognized as a legend...

It's cool man. I'm gonna be telling my grandkids about how Dave Chappelle was the shit. When I was just a pothead teenager he was doing comedy that obviously spoke to a whole generation of pothead teenagers, but always a cut above the rest, just a lot more insightful and funny, even if they were just jokes about babies selling weed in the ghetto. And then I we grow up and his comedy matures with us.

Hell yeah

snippet.textDisplay: There are very few TRULY great comedians, but Dave Chappelle is among them. I know life is short, but hopefully Dave's longers longer than most. The world started going downhill after we lost George Carlin. There was no one there to hold a mirror up and challenge the absurdity our society had come to. Dave fills those shoes now, and I need him to wear them just a little while longer, and a little more frequently.
